 Early Eighteenth-Century Venice -- t14 Literary Motifs in Metastasio’s and Jommelli’s Ciro riconosciuto -- t15 Producing Stars in Dramma per musica -- t16 The Pre-revolutionary Origins of ‘Terrorisme musical’ -- t17 Pieces into Works: Cherubini’s Substitute Arias for the Théâtre Feydeau -- t18 At the Tavern with Manzoni and Verdi: I promessi sposi and the Dramaturgy of La forza del destino -- tIV The Crisis of Modernity -- t19 The Acoustic Proximity of Temporal Distance: Auratic Sonority in Mahler’s Lieder eines fahrenden Gesellen -- t20 Creating a Concept of ‘Nazi Musicology’ -- t21 Et in Arcadia adhuc: Observations on the Continuing Evolution of the ‘Pastoral Idea’ -- tEpilogue -- tReinhard Strohm: List of Publications -- tIndex -- tTabula Gratulatoria0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEssays dealing with the controversial concept of the "work", and how far social and cultural practices are integral to it.The linking theme of the essays collected here is the intersection of musical work with social and cultural practice. Inspired by Professor Strohm's ideas, as is fitting in a volume in his honour, leading scholars in the field explore diverse conceptualizations of the "work" within the contexts of a specific repertory, over four main sections. Music in Theory and Practice studies the link between treatises and musical practice, and analyses how historicalwritings can reveal period views on the "work" in music before 1800. Art and Social Process: Music in Court and Urban Societies looks at the social and cultural practices informing composition from the late Renaissance until the mid-eighteenth century, and interrogates current notions of canon formation and the exchange between local and foreign traditions. Creating an Opera Industry focuses on how genre and artistic autonomy were defined in operas from diverse eras and countries, explaining the role of literature and politics in this process. Finally, The Crisis of Modernity treats nineteenth-century music, offering new models for "work" and "context" to challenge reigning theories of the meaning of these terms. CONTRIBUTORS: AMNON SHILOAH, ANNA MARIA BUSSE BERGER, MARGARET BENT, EDWARD WICKHAM, BONNIE J. BLACKBURN, DAVID BRYANT, ELENA QUARANTA, OWEN REES, ALINA ZORAWSKA-WITKOWSKA, ELLEN T. HARRIS, CHRISTOPH WOLFF, NORBERT DUBOWY, MICHAEL TALBOT, MELANIA BUCCIARELLI, FRANCESCA MENCHELLI-BUTTINI, BERTA JONCUS, MICHEL NOIRAY, MICHAEL FEND, EMANUELE SENICI, FEDERICO CELESTINI, PAMELA POTTER, GIOVANNI MORELLI, JANET SMITH  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aMusicxPhilosophy and aesthetics. 0aMusicxSocial aspects. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aEuropean music.  aartistic autonomy.  agenre.  ahistorical writings.  amusic work.  amusical treatises.  anineteenth-century music.  asocial and cultural practice.1 aBent, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlackburn, Bonnie J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlackburn, Bonnie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryant, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBucciarelli, Melania, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBucciarelli, Melania, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBusse Berger, Anna Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCelestini, Federico, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDubowy, Norbert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFend, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Ell